<div id="node-6" class="section-3">
  <h1 class="book-heading">Resources</h1>
  <div class="field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden"><div class="field__items"><div class="field__item even"><h2>Guides and tools for organisers</h2>

<h3>Events</h3>

<ul><li><a href="https://adacamp.org/" rel="nofollow">AdaCamp Toolkit</a> - how to organise an unconference, with a focus on feminism. Includes guidance for venue planning, policies, and event communications.</li>
	<li><a href="http://scottberkun.com/2006/how-to-run-a-great-unconference-session/" rel="nofollow">Scott Berkun - How to run a great unconference session</a> - session formats, and suggestions for hosts.</li>
</ul><h3>Online</h3>

<ul><li><a href="http://mappingmashups.net/2012/12/14/how-to-host-a-geowebchat/" rel="nofollow">Mapping Mashups - How to host a #geowebchat</a></li>
	<li><a href="http://www.socialmediaexaminer.com/twitter-chat-guide/" rel="nofollow">Social Media Examiner - 5 Steps to Hosting Successful Twitter Chats</a></li>
	<li><a href="https://www.theengineroom.org/usefull-online-meeting-tools/" rel="nofollow">The Engine Room - From ad-hoc meetings with a few colleagues to webinar-style large meetings, here are some tools we’re finding useful</a></li>
	<li><a href="https://gendersec.tacticaltech.org/wiki/index.php/Complete_manual" rel="nofollow">Tactical Technology Collective - Zen and the art of making tech work for you</a> - how to create safe online and offline spaces for women and trans* activists, human rights defenders and others.</li>
	<li><a href="https://ssd.eff.org/en" rel="nofollow">Electronic Frontier Foundation - Surveillance Self-Defense</a> - how to practise safer online communication.</li>
	<li><a href="https://coralproject.net/" rel="nofollow">The Coral Project</a> - software tools for building better online communities.</li>
	<li><a href="https://pages.18f.gov/guides/" rel="nofollow">18F Guides</a> - Guides to content, accessibility, best practices for digital service teams.</li>
</ul><h3>General</h3>

<ul><li><a href="http://trapese.clearerchannel.org/resources.php" rel="nofollow">Do It Yourself: A Handbook For Changing Our World</a> - Edited by Trapese (Pluto Press, 2007) (free download)</li>
	<li><a href="http://beautifultrouble.org/introduction/" rel="nofollow">Beautiful Trouble: A Toolbox for Revolution</a> - Edited by Andrew Boyd and Dave Oswald Mitchell (OR Books, 2012) (free online)</li>
	<li><a href="http://civicmediaproject.org/works/civic-media-project/learning-guide" rel="nofollow">Civic Media Project learning guide</a> - identify issues and address them through civic media projects (includes case studies).</li>
	<li><a href="http://byanymedia.org/works/mapp/book-companion" rel="nofollow">By Any Media Necessary: Mapping Youth and Participatory Politics companion reader</a> - case studies of youth media projects.</li>
	<li><a href="http://elab.emerson.edu/learning/#guidebooks" rel="nofollow">Engagement Lab guidebooks</a> - experimenting with play and technology to engage people in real-world processes.</li>
	<li><a href="http://schoolofdata.org/data-expeditions/guide-for-guides/" rel="nofollow">School of Data's Guide for Guides</a> - tips for running a data quest</li>
	<li><a href="https://open.bufferapp.com/transparent-feedback-experiment/" rel="nofollow">Buffer - When We Took Transparency Too Far: The Transparent Feedback Experiment</a> - how transparency in an organisation can fail.</li>
	<li><a href="https://opensource.com/business/15/8/5-open-source-alternatives-trello" rel="nofollow">Opensource.com - 5 open source alternatives to Trello</a> - task list/project management tools.</li>
	<li><a href="http://opentranscripts.org" rel="nofollow">Open Transcripts</a></li>
	<li><a href="http://zararah.net/blog/2015/10/08/open-vs-closed/" rel="nofollow">Open communities vs closed communities - what's more inclusive?</a> - Zara Rahman (2015)</li>
	<li><a href="http://sarah.thesharps.us/2015/10/06/what-makes-a-good-community/" rel="nofollow">What makes a good community?</a> - Sarah Sharp (2015)</li>
	<li><a href="http://www.salon.com/2015/10/28/i_wanted_to_be_a_supporter_of_survivors_on_campus_and_a_good_teacher_i_didnt_realize_just_how_impossible_this_would_be" rel="nofollow">My trigger-warning disaster: "9 1/2 Weeks," "The Wire" and how coddled young radicals got discomfort all wrong</a> - Rani Neutill (2015)</li>
	<li><a href="http://www.fabriders.net/training/" rel="nofollow">FabRiders Training Hub</a> - resources for using <span>data effectively for advocacy, social change and social justice</span></li>
	<li><span><a href="http://datatherapy.org" rel="nofollow">datatherapy</a> - </span>processes, tools and tutorials to help you present and share your data in creative ways</li>
	<li><a href="http://diytoolkit.org/tools/" rel="nofollow">Development Impact &amp; You</a> - toolkit on how to invent, adopt or adapt ideas that can deliver better results</li>
	<li><a href="http://allourideas.org/" rel="nofollow">All Our Ideas</a> - pairwise wiki surveys with crowdsourced questions (<a href="http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0123483" rel="nofollow">paper</a>)</li>
	<li><a href="http://www.thesis.mlamadrid.com/?page_id=4" rel="nofollow">Social Design Toolkit</a> (Change for Social Design)</li>
	<li><a href="http://wenger-trayner.com/resources/publications/evaluation-framework/" rel="nofollow">Promoting and assessing value creation in communities and networks: a conceptual framework</a> - Wenger, Trayner, de Laat (2011)</li>
	<li><a href="https://medium.com/@SeanBlanda/the-other-side-is-not-dumb-2670c1294063#.q93hf4r6f" rel="nofollow">The "Other Side" Is Not Dumb</a> - Sean Blanda (2016)</li>
	<li><a href="http://everydayfeminism.com/2015/09/social-justice-less-elitist/" rel="nofollow">9 Ways We Can Make Social Justice Movements Less Elitist and More Accessible</a> - Kai Cheng Thom (2015)</li>
</ul><p><span class="highlight">@todo</span></p>

<ul><li>Separate guides and tools into stages of event: planning, execution, documentation</li>
</ul><h2>List of advocacy, volunteer and civic media organisations</h2>

<p><span class="highlight">@todo</span></p>

<ul><li>Compile a list of significant organisations; 122,000 NPOs in South Africa according to SANGONeT<a class="see-footnote" id="footnoteref1_psgloyj" title="http://www.ngopulse.org/about" href="http://dandelion.liquidfridge.co.za/#footnote1_psgloyj">1</a>.</li>
	<li>Entries should be categorised/tagged according to area of focus, e.g. social, economic, political, ecological, and location, so that it's easy to match relevant organisations in local community with topic of discussion.</li>
